I am all for calling out bad brands - we do it on Yelp, Amazon, etc.

But if you participate in toxic cancel culture by jumping on bandwagons - GrowTFU.

Get the facts.

If they’re trash, there’s evidence.

if they’re not, there’s that too.

Receipts matter, and I learned a long time ago - in the corporate world - that keeping them is valuable.

Perception can be either a crazy mirror or an honest one.

Context matters.

Get to doing your own great work and run people out of town by NOT giving them money, time or energy anymore.

Such a messy online culture.

That’s why I don’t play over here on these internet streets - never have and never will.

If you call out people without context, facts and evidence and aren’t willing to come to a public debate with both parties involved, you’re part of the problem, not the solution.

Leaving people with dignity while being honest makes us civilized.

Being this way has made me lose friends and business colleagues. But let me tell you what:

I wont drag you publicly until I face you privately. 

Leaders don’t gossip. They lean into conflict and decide whether or not a relationship is worth saving.

I have a list of folks I would never invite to my house. 

But I can’t control the drama and trauma you allow people to dog whistle you with.

Grown business is beautiful business.

Thank you for listening to my Ted Talk.

I divorced “resolutions” a long time ago.

Instead, I take a values-driven ME-Retreat and:

1. “Reset my priorities” after realistic reflection from the past year, then

2.  Create *clarifying intentions* that I want to embody and experience this year, then

3. Sort these clarifying intentions into the 4 categories of my life that matter to me: Health, Wealth, Self and Relationships, then

4. List 1-3 *honest outcomes* that would show me (not anyone else) that I was committed to my clarifying intentions and assign them to my 4 categories, then

5. *Review my desires* by having a ME-Retreat every month to check in if these clarifying intentions and honest outcomes are still values-driven for me, based on my ability to be committed to them.

The ME-Retreat is simply a block of time I connect with myself in quiet, uninterrupted time. Sometimes I go for a day trip to do it. Most times I just build it into a Monday or Friday (my creative flow days) in my office, with some music and nothing else. 

Examples of my system:

Reset my priorities: my body requires different things than it has in the past. 

Clarifying intention: nourish and move my body in ways that are appropriate for what she needs now, not what I wish she was or was before.

Honest outcome: 30g of protein consumed per day. 2-3 days or more of strength training per week. Drink water before anything else when I wake up in the morning.

Review my desires: how often did I stay in integrity with myself this past month? What did I choose to interfere with my honest outcomes that I said I wanted? Did I reset the appropriate priorities to support me in achieving what I said I wanted?

This takes 10 mins every month to do. It’s not that deep and it’s mainly a conversation I’m willing to have with myself every month.
